      "message": "If there is no default timeout set socket.getdefaulttimeout() returns None which results in a different behaviour to what happens when no timeout is set. Hence the use of socket._GLOBAL_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT which is not None.\n\nMy understanding of the C library behind socket.py and socket.py is that if you pass in a timeout of anything other than socket._GLOBAL_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT the settimeout method will be called on the socket option and with the following args will take various actions on the socket:\n\n   None -- no timeout, blocking mode; same as setblocking(True)\n   0.0  -- non-blocking mode; same as setblocking(False)\n   \u003e 0  -- timeout mode; operations time out after timeout seconds\n   \u003c 0  -- illegal; raises an exception\n\nSo you pass in a timeout\u003dsocket.getdefaulttimeout(), this will always enable blocking mode, where as timeout\u003dsocket._GLOBAL_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT will result in non-blocking mode or immediate return, timeout \u003e 0 means block until timeout reached.\n\nSo either must avoid setting a timeout if it\u0027s not provided, or ensure that we use the default of socket._GLOBAL_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT and only override if replaced in order to allow for existing default behaviour and still allow for timeouts.",
